          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 20px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What is the Lorenz curve?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-24-3.png" alt="What is the Lorenz curve?" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000"> 
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The Lorenz curve is a graphical representation used to measure income or wealth inequality within a population. Developed by economist Max Lorenz in 1905, the curve plots the cumulative percentage of total income earned against the cumulative percentage of the population, ranked from the poorest to the richest.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          In a perfectly equal society, the Lorenz curve would be a 45-degree line, known as the line of equality, where each percentage of the population earns an equal share of income. However, the curve typically bows below this line, indicating inequality. The further the curve is from the line of equality, the greater the level of inequality.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          
          Economists often use the Lorenz curve alongside the Gini coefficient, which quantifies inequality based on the area between the curve and the line of equality. This tool is crucial for understanding income disparities and shaping policies aimed at reducing inequality.
         </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
